# LLM Arena Development Rules

## Code Style & Organization

### General
- Follow the Airbnb Style Guide for code formatting
- Use PascalCase for React component file names (e.g., UserCard.tsx, not user-card.tsx)
- Prefer named exports for components
- Follow Next.js patterns and use the App Router
- Correctly determine when to use server vs. client components in Next.js

### Styling
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling
- Use Shadcn UI components based on Radix UI primitives
- Maintain consistent spacing and component styling

### Data & Forms
- Use TanStack Query (react-query) for frontend data fetching
- Use React Hook Form for form handling
- Use Zod for validation

## Software Development Principles

### Separation of Concerns
- Organize UI elements into reusable components
- Maintain clear separation between app logic, components, and utilities
- Use React Context for state management across components

### Single Responsibility Principle
- Create small, focused utility files (e.g., jwt.ts, mongo.ts)
- Each API route should handle a specific functionality
- Design UI components with specific, well-defined purposes

### DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- Abstract common UI elements into reusable components
- Extract common operations into utility functions
- Manage shared state through context providers

### Error Handling
- Implement proper error handling in API routes
- Use toast notifications for user feedback on errors
- Validate required environment variables

### Progressive Enhancement
- Use feature flags for in-development functionality
- Implement mobile-first responsive design
- Provide fallbacks for when certain features are unavailable

## Git Workflow

### Commit Style
- Follow Conventional Commits specification:
  - feat: A new feature or enhancement
  - fix: A bug fix
  - refactor: Code changes that neither fix bugs nor add features
  - docs: Documentation changes
  - style: Changes that don't affect code functionality
  - test: Adding or correcting tests
  - chore: Changes to build process or auxiliary tools
- Include detailed descriptions for complex changes

### Branch Strategy
- Create feature branches from main
- Use pull requests to merge features back to main
- Maintain a clean commit history